{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16213"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16213"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.44,0.26,0.15,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64348"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8904"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"595"},{"type":"tags","id":"3884"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"8156"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21188"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64348"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA breast tissue biopsy specimen from a 45-year-old woman shows dense periductal lymphocytic infiltration with plasma cells. The ducts appear normal in size without secretory changes. There is no evidence of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes these histological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lactational mastitis","Non-lactational mastitis","Fibrocystic change","Intraductal papilloma","Fat necrosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological features described are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-lactational mastitis\u003C/strong\u003E, showing dense lymphoplasmacytic infiltration around normal-sized ducts without evidence of lactational changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactational mastitis\u003C/strong\u003E would show dilated ducts containing milk protein secretions with predominantly neutrophilic inflammation. \u003Cstrong\u003EFibrocystic change\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows cyst formation, ductal hyperplasia, and stromal fibrosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E would demonstrate papillary projections within dilated ducts. \u003Cstrong\u003EFat necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E shows necrotic adipose tissue with lipid-laden macrophages and foreign body giant cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-lactational mastitis commonly occurs in non-pregnant women and can be associated with periductal inflammation, which may be related to smoking, nipple piercing, or other local factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-lactational mastitis typically shows dense lymphocytic infiltration and periductal inflammation without lactational changes in breast tissue.","Lactational mastitis shows dilated ducts with milk protein secretions and neutrophilic inflammation."],"references":["\u0022Histopathology of mastitis\u0022 by \u0022EDWARD.THE.MED.GOOD\u0022 is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Granulomatous_Lobular_Mastitis_and_Cystic_Neutrophilic_Granulomatous_Mastitis.tif?page=1","Blackmon MM, Nguyen H, Mukherji P. Acute Mastitis. [Updated 2023 Jul 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557782/","Zucca-Matthes G, Urban C, Vallejo A. Anatomy of the nipple and breast ducts. Gland Surg. 2016 Feb;5(1):32-6. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2227-684X.2015.05.10. PMID: 26855906; PMCID: PMC4716863","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16213"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21214"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21214"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ggW7JYdOIWp9AdOSWS31QJyQ7sIFSw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ggW7JYdOIWp9AdOSWS31QJyQ7sIFSw.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1242,"height":914}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49780"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T13:04:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T21:00:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8904"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64348"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations